Date: 0/0/1959
Source: History of New Zealand
Author: SINCLAIR
Vol / Page: 182
Edition:
Quote: Since it was distinctly possible that Stout might split the Liberal Party over this issue [temperance], Seddon was in 1893 obliged to forestall him by introducing a `local option'. This gave the voters the right to decide on the continuation or reduction of liquor licences in their electorates; a three-fifths majority could prohibit the sale of liquor altogether.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1982
Source: Collins Concise English Dictionary
Author:
Vol / Page: 661
Edition:
Quote: local option n. (esp. in Scotland, New Zealand, and the U.S.) the privilege of a municipality, county, etc., to determine by referendum whether a particular activity, esp. the sale of liquor, shall be permitted there.
Notes: nf. 1986 NZPOD; 1985 Collins NZ Compact Dict. 288]

